Now this is a real metaprogramming interview question.

They want you to implement dynamic getter & setter methods using method_missing.

Requirement:

x.demo = "abc"   # => should return nil
x.demo           # => "abc"

So basically:

If method ends with =, treat it like a setter

Store the value somewhere

Later, when getter is called, return stored value

Let’s build this properly.

🧠 Step 1 — Understand What Ruby Sends

When you write:

x.demo = "abc"

Ruby internally calls:

method_missing(:demo=, "abc")

Notice:

Method name becomes :demo=

Argument is "abc"

When you call:

x.demo

Ruby calls:

method_missing(:demo)

So we need to handle both cases.

✅ Final Working Solution
class User
  def initialize(name)
    @name = name
    @dynamic_attributes = {}
  end

  def greet
    puts "Hello #{@name}"
  end

  def method_missing(method_name, *args, &block)
    method_name = method_name.to_s

    if method_name.end_with?("=")
      # Setter
      attribute = method_name.chomp("=")
      @dynamic_attributes[attribute] = args.first
      nil
    elsif @dynamic_attributes.key?(method_name)
      # Getter
      @dynamic_attributes[method_name]
    else
      puts "This #{method_name} is not present"
    end
  end

  def respond_to_missing?(method_name, include_private = false)
    true
  end
end
🔎 Test It
x = User.new("Shubham")

x.demo = "abc"
# => nil

x.demo
# => "abc"

x.age
# => This age is not present

Works exactly as interviewer asked.

🧠 What We Did
1️⃣ Stored dynamic attributes in a hash
@dynamic_attributes = {}
2️⃣ If method ends with =
method_name.end_with?("=")

We treat it as setter.

3️⃣ Remove = using:
method_name.chomp("=")
4️⃣ Store value in hash
@dynamic_attributes[attribute] = args.first
5️⃣ Getter returns stored value
🎯 Why Setter Returns nil?

Because interviewer specifically asked:

x.demo = "abc"  # => nil

Normally Ruby setters return the assigned value:

@var = 10  # returns 10

But we explicitly return nil.

🚀 Bonus (Interview Level Improvement)

Instead of using method_missing forever,
we can dynamically define the method after first call:

define_singleton_method(attribute) do
  @dynamic_attributes[attribute]
end

This improves performance.

But usually interviewer is happy with first solution.

